Why America Should Not Reelect President Bush
I have never particularly engaged myself politically, but these are not normal times.
President George W. Bush endangers the security of the United States and the world and simultaneously undermines American values.
Because of my opposition to him, I have been demonized by Bush's campaign team.
President Bush ran in 2000 with a campaign promise of a foreign policy of "humble".
If he is reelected, this will be a vote for the Bush doctrine of preemptive war - and the invasion of Iraq - and the world will have to live with the consequences.
By rejecting Bush's policies at the ballot boxes, America has a chance to regain the respect and support of the world.
The terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, required a strong response.
They have, however, also led to the critical process so indispensable to democracy - the comprehensive and honest discussion of pending issues - being set aside.
Bush has silenced criticism by declaring it unpatriotic.
For a period of 18 months following September 11, he has managed to suppress all dissent.
In this way, he has led America in the wrong direction.
Indeed, Bush has played directly into Osama bin Laden's hands.
The invasion of Afghanistan - where bin Laden lived and Al Qaeda maintained its training camps - was justified.
The invasion of Iraq was not.
He was Bush's unintended gift to bin Laden.
Immediately following September 11, spontaneous expressions of sympathy for America emerged all over the world.
These have been replaced by widespread bitterness.
Clearly more people than on September 11 are today willing to risk their lives to kill Americans.
Bush likes to claim that terrorists hate Americans for what they are - a freedom-loving people - and not for what they do.
War and occupation, however, produce innocent victims.
We Americans count our fallen soldiers - more than 1,000 in Iraq.
The rest of the world also counts the Iraqis killed every day - perhaps twenty times as many.
Similarly, the torture of detainees at the Abu Ghraib prison was not the work of a few "bad apples".
It was part of a system set up by Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld for dealing with detainees.
The world public condemns America, and our troops in Iraq pay the price for it.
Bush has convinced people that America's security is in good hands by addressing the fears caused by the attacks of September 11.
In times of danger, people gather around their flag, and Bush has exploited this by fostering a sense of threat.
His campaign assumes that people are ultimately not interested in the truth and will almost believe anything if it is repeated often enough.
Something must be wrong with America if we fall for this.
For example, about 40% of all Americans still believe that Saddam Hussein had something to do with September 11, although the September 11th Commission - appointed by Bush and chaired by a Republican - clearly determined that no such connection existed.
One wants to scream: "Wake up, America.
Don't you realize that we are being led by the nose?"
The war in Iraq was based from the beginning until its end - if it ever finds an end - on false premises.
It was a war of one's own decision, not out of necessity.
Moreover, America went to war under a pretext: weapons of mass destruction could not be found, and the connection to Al Qaeda cannot be proven.
Bush then claimed that America went to war to free Iraq.
But you cannot impose democracy on anyone by force.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and the Iraqis - and the world - can be glad to be rid of him.
But America had the duty to ensure justice and order; instead, we watched helplessly as Baghdad and other cities were looted.
If we had really been concerned about the Iraqi people, we would have had to provide a larger number of soldiers for the occupation.
We would not only have had to protect the Ministry of Oil, but also other ministries, museums, and hospitals.
Worse still: Where American soldiers encountered resistance, they used methods - such as breaking into private homes and mistreating prisoners - that shocked and humiliated the population and thus generated resentment and anger.
The retreats and blunders of the Bush administration are legion.
First, the Iraqi army was disbanded, then America tried to rebuild it.
First, the USA tried to eliminate the Baathists, then America sought their help.
When the uprisings could no longer be controlled, America installed an Iraqi government.
The man chosen to be their leader was a CIA protégé with the reputation of a "strong man" - anything but a democratic decision.
Despite the efforts of Bush's campaign team to spin the situation, the situation in Iraq is bleak.
A large part of the western part of the country has been left to insurgents. The prospects for holding free and fair elections in January are rapidly fading.
Civil war threatens.
Bush's war in Iraq has also caused immeasurable damage to America, weakened its military power, and undermined the morale of the troops.
Before the war, America could project an image of overwhelming strength.
Today no longer.
Afghanistan is slipping out of control.
North Korea, Iran, Pakistan, and other countries are pursuing nuclear programs with renewed energy.
One can criticize the Bush administration on many other political issues, but none is as significant as Iraq.
The costs of the war so far amount to nearly 200 billion dollars and will continue to rise, because the invasion of Iraq was much easier than the withdrawal will be.
Bush has baited John Kerry to explain what he would do differently.
Kerry responded that he would have done everything differently and that he would be in a better position to free us from our entanglement.
But it will not be easy for him either, because America is stuck in a quagmire.
Leading military experts and diplomats have desperately warned Bush not to march into Iraq.
He ignored them.
He suppressed the critical process with the argument that any criticism of the commander-in-chief would endanger US troops.
But this is Bush's war, and he should be held accountable for it.
The Americans should take a moment to pause and ask themselves: To whom do we owe this mess?
A moment of reflection should raise another question: Does Bush's cowboy behavior qualify him to remain America's supreme commander?
